metadata.name: E=B; #141
metadata.description:
- Last day with the dying planet -

A sentimental start.

It is the last day of this planet, you once lived and shared so many meaningful memories.

Take a last good look at the places of the planet. Look to the far side. You see people were leaving already. But you loved the planet so much that you dare to risk and stay a bit longer before you leave.

This moment becomes bottomless. Landscapes glitter vividly with altered gradients, fog emits at the far end of the land, and Energy leaks and escapes from the core, thru the cracks in form of aurora structure.

It is a mix of sadness, grief, missing, and anxiety.
It is the end.
It is breathtaking.
It makes you hesitate.

// About the scene
The planet was vast.
You may experience Rocky Sierra, Fluidy Mountains, Wide Dunes, and even Calm Ocean.

The Breakdown
In the rare case, you might be able to see a highly pixelated/extreme wide/flat landscape with finely emitted aurora, which is considered a rare scene. i.e. absolute strength of light vs breakdown of limited matters.

// About the presentation style
The Texture & The Drawing : Heavily inspired by pencil sketching techniques that emphasize shading and outline relationship towards an angular light source.

Apply color scheme from other Astro objects to give an alternative look for the planet.

The Animation Sequence: Custom storytelling algorithms combine the formation of the aurora, landscape, and scene detail all in a timeline. The resulting sequential narrative style illustrates the history of the landscape and the aurora formation.

Not just giving the collector the final look but also sharing the cause and reason of such composition.

The Tiny Zoom: A tiny zoom-out movement is implemented in the piece to echo the theme of the piece. i.e. leaving and departing the planet.

// About the Music
Two theme songs were made for this piece.

Theme I: [Solitude]
Theme II: [Fragmented]

Both songs were made to present the process of departure: the sleep of the planet and the awakening of the observer.

// Metaphor
We face departure and arrival all the time. They might be the best or the worst memories of our life. Whether you are willing to or not.

The ending is an ongoing process and on the other side of the Ending comes the beginning.

It is ok to be sentimental.

// Control
Best viewed in large and wide proportion.
(Open in new window)

[S] - save the scene once the drawing stops
[L] - leave and take a look at other places
[Mouse Click] - click twice to initiate music. then click one to mute/show


- 與垂死星球的最後一天 -

從感傷開始。

這是你曾經生活在的星球之最後一天，你們的關係將要結束，許多有意義的回憶也將封印成回憶。

看看遠方。其他人已經開始離開了。
你還留著，想好好看看這個星球。

你請願冒險，也要在離開之前多停留一段時間。

此刻像是無限。景觀隨著漸變的顏色而變得更加生動，在陸地的遠端散發出最後的火霧，能量從核心洩漏，以極光狀的結構從裂縫中逸出。

它是悲傷、內疚、思念和焦慮的混合體。
這是結束。
但又嘆為觀止。
讓你猶豫不決。

// 關於現場
這個星球曾經很大
您會經歷到寂靜的岳峰、流動的山脈、寬闊的沙丘以及平靜的海洋。

罕見的一刻 - 物質崩壞
在極少數情況下，您可能會看到極寬/平坦/鋸齒化的景觀與高像素細膩的極光並存，即光的絕對強度與有限的物質瓦解。

// 關於演示風格
紋理與繪畫風格 : 深受鉛筆素描技術的啟發，這些技術強調與角光源的陰影和輪廓關係。

應用其他天文物體的配色方案，為地球提供另一種外觀。

動畫序列 : 自定義敘事算法將極光、風景和場景細節的形成全部結合在一個時間軸中。由此產生的順序敘述風格，說明了景觀的歷史和極光的形成。

不僅給收藏家最終的外觀，而且還分享了這種構圖的原因和原因。

小變焦 : 作品中實施了微小的縮小運鏡，以呼應作品的主題 - 離開。

// 關於音樂
為作品製作了兩首主題曲。

主題一：【獨】
主題二：【碎】

兩首歌表達/呈現離開的過程：星球的沉睡和觀察者的覺醒。

// 隱喻
不管你願不願意，我們無時無刻都面臨著離去和到來。離去前它們是我們一生中最美好/最糟糕的回憶。

結局是一維，離開是二維的，另一端叫作開始。

覺得感傷是ok 的。

// 控制
但在大寬視窗下視覺效果最好
(Open in new window)

[S] - 繪圖停止後存取畫作
[L] - 離開去其他地方看看
[鼠標單擊] - 單擊兩次以啟動音樂。 然後單擊一個靜音/顯示

metadata.name: Garden Of Symmetry #320
metadata.description:
Sometimes, things look better when seen from the distance. Not from far away, but from a length that allows one to see what’s possibly underneath. Or, you may not see anything. Instead, you can just enjoy things falling into place.

Get a pack of shattered glass, snow, or ice*, uncovering a pattern. Or an axis of dancing geometries. Enter the Garden of Symmetry.

The graphic is a plottable SVG file in A3 format, ready to be drawn using a pen plotter. In the full screen view, click somewhere on the artwork to download a copy.

I recommend to optimize the SVG before plotting, i.e. using vpype. I also recommend to draw the graphic using 0.7mm pen.

License: CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/ - @jakub_antolak

———
*choose your option

metadata.name: The Streamline #136
metadata.description:
Form, an essential aspect in architectural design, refers to the shape, structure and arrangement of spaces or objects. Witnessing how forms work in a space can also be a transcendental experience, where one can sense the presence of a form, not only seeing it.

As there are many ways to create it, Form can appear as an internal structure, as an external shape of a two dimensional plane that envelopes a three dimensional mass, or a repetition of a two dimensional shape that stacks on an axis and moves to a certain direction. With so many ways to create shape, there is no law dictating that shape has to be rigid. And this is where Milunic and Gehry's design for the Dancing House comes in as an inspiration for this work.

A change in the political axis from one of a regime to a parliamentary democracy was what influenced the architects to juxtapose two different energies together. With its dynamic and static shapes in tandem, Dancing House is one iconic proof that form can also be pliable and animated.

------------
Press [s] to save captured image
------------
It may take a few seconds to render, depending on the device.
works better with chrome

created using WEBGL on p5.js
dirbots - Feb23

metadata.name: A Pocket Full of Wonder #107
metadata.description:
"A Pocket Full of Wonder" invites you to embark on a journey where the boundaries between technology and art are blurred. 

Here, machine-generated images serve as a foundation for a vibrant and dynamic world of code-driven art. This union of artificial intelligence and creative coding evokes a sense of wonder and discovery, as each piece reveals the beauty that can be born from the interplay of technology and art. 

With "A Pocket Full of Wonder", we explore the limitless possibilities that emerge when we allow technology to augment and enhance our artistic visions.

metadata.name: Fractured Time #142
metadata.description:
Composed of bent shards and twisted slivers, Fractured Time is an exploration of how we might visually perceive gravity's effects on linear time.

Like an astronaut who gets too close to a blackhole, how would we make sense of this four-dimensional time-space experience? The pieces of the world as we know it would no longer align. Everything would stretch, splinter, pulse, and fray around us.

This is my attempt to capture that mind-bending trip in two dimensions.

Press [s] to save a .png at 4000 x 4000 pixels
Press [f] to open fullscreen

32 Color Palettes

metadata.name: The Differential #60
metadata.description:
Noise forms along a crystal edge; points delineate the surface in a thousand clustered moments, each one its polar opposite, joined and viewed from a distance by separate, sylph-like fragments of an instant's slow tick.

At the event horizon, the escape velocity is equal to the speed of light. Since general relativity states that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light, nothing inside the event horizon can ever cross the boundary and escape beyond it, including light.
